If Rails is using static hardcoded certificate (not metadata-based), and ADFS rotates certificate at midnight…

What must your team do immediately to avoid outage?

(Think operationally.)

🔐 Scenario

Rails is using static hardcoded IdP certificate

Active Directory Federation Services rotates to a new signing certificate at midnight

ADFS starts signing SAML responses with the NEW certificate

Rails still trusts only the OLD certificate

What happens?

❌ Signature verification fails
❌ All SSO logins break

🚨 What Must Be Done Immediately?

You must:

1️⃣ Get the NEW signing certificate from ADFS

From federation metadata URL

Or from IT team

2️⃣ Update Rails configuration:

idp_cert: NEW_CERT

3️⃣ Deploy the change

4️⃣ Restart application

Then logins work again.

❌ Why “Generate New Certificate” Is Incorrect

Because:

The signing certificate belongs to ADFS (IdP)

Rails (SP) does NOT control IdP signing keys

Rails only trusts/verifies

Only the IdP generates signing certificates.

🧠 Correct Operational Thinking

If static certificate setup is used:

When IdP rotates:

👉 App team must update trusted certificate immediately
👉 Redeploy
👉 Clear incident

This is why static cert configuration is risky.

🏗 What A Senior Engineer Would Say

If we are using a statically configured IdP certificate and ADFS rotates its signing certificate, we must immediately update the trusted certificate in our Rails configuration and redeploy. To avoid this operational risk, it's better to consume IdP metadata dynamically and support multiple signing certificates.

🔥 That shows architecture maturity + operational awareness.

💎 Even More Senior Insight

In production, teams usually:

Monitor certificate expiration dates

Schedule update before expiration

Avoid emergency midnight outages

